Good call—locking the kernel on Proxmox VE is one of those “save yourself later pain” moves, especially for a homelab where a random kernel update can break networking, drivers, or VMs.

🧠 What “locking the kernel” actually does

It prevents apt upgrade from installing a newer kernel automatically, so your system stays stable.

✅ Step 1 — See your current kernel
uname -r

You’ll get something like:

6.8.4-3-pve
🔒 Step 2 — Lock the kernel packages

Run:

apt-mark hold proxmox-kernel-*
apt-mark hold pve-kernel-*

This tells APT:

“Do NOT upgrade these packages unless I explicitly allow it.”

🔍 Step 3 — Verify it worked
apt-mark showhold

You should see:

proxmox-kernel-...
pve-kernel-...
⚠️ Important nuance (this is where people mess up)

This locks future updates, but:

It does NOT remove already-installed newer kernels
It does NOT stop Proxmox from listing newer kernels
🧹 Optional (but recommended): Remove extra kernels

List installed kernels:

dpkg --list | grep pve-kernel

Remove older ones (keep your current + one backup):

apt remove pve-kernel-<old-version>
🚨 If you ever WANT to upgrade later

Unlock:

apt-mark unhold proxmox-kernel-*
apt-mark unhold pve-kernel-*

Then upgrade normally.
